thread.title: Washington governor honors dog who protected trapped friend
thread.title_full: Washington governor honors dog who protected trapped friend

author: RACHEL LA CORTE Associated Press
title: Washington governor honors dog who protected trapped friend
text: October 15, 2015 Washington governor honors dog who protected trapped friend Washington State Gov. Jay Inslee pats Phoebe, left, on Thursday at the Governor's Office in Olympia. Inslee awarded Phoebe's best friend, Tillie, right, the Washingtonian of the Day award for her bravery and loyalty in rescuing Phoebe, who fell into an old cistern. Tillie stayed by her side for a week, leaving only briefly each day to try and find help. The dogs were found hungry and cold, but safe, on Vashon Island. Lui Kit Wong The News Tribune B.J. Duft, second from left, of Vashon Island, Wash., holds his dogs Tillie, right, and Phoebe, as they visit with Washington Gov. Jay Inslee, left, Thursday, Oct. 15, 2015, in his office in Olympia, Wash. Tillie was given the "Washingtonian of the Day" award by the governor for standing by Phoebe for nearly a week after they strayed from their home and Phoebe fell into a old cistern. The pair were eventually located by searchers, with Tillie loyally remaining by the edge of the cistern until help arrived. Ted S. Warren AP Photo FILE - In this Sept. 15, 2015, file photo, provided by Amy Carey of Vashon Island Pet Protectors, a setter mix dog named Tillie, left, watches over Phoebe, a basset hound who was trapped after falling into cistern shown at right nearly a week earlier, just before being rescued by searchers on Vashon Island, Wash. Both dogs are owned by BJ Duft, who was on hand, Thursday, Oct. 15, 2015, when Tillie was honored in Olympia, Wash., by Gov. Jay Inslee for her loyalty to Phoebe.
